Parliament rejects amendment to release Tymoshenko
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine in the course of amendments to the Criminal Procedure Code rejected an attempt to cancel the article, according to which the opposition leader, Yulia Tymoshenko, was convicted.
The amendment, which would lead to the release of the former prime minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the bill on mitigating sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The verdict is not final; the court will consider Tymoshenko’s appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Criminal Procedure Code, according to which the former prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to be ratified.
