Ambassador to the European Union:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unwelcome and skeptical of the euro.
“The Lisbon Treaty has caused considerable disagreements between the individual organizations.”
“I did not expect such a cruel war.”
"It will take five or six years before the situation at least somehow stabilizes, calms down and all players get used to their new roles," EU ambassador Milena Witsenova began her lecture at the law school.
She proved how much she adheres to her motto "Clearly and openly about Europe" in the first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simply and clearly that many lecturers from the KU Law School would envy.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
“First, critics said he’s an ordinary gray office mouse that can’t perform any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he did with his role.”
“He is a man who can listen to twenty-seven member countries at the same time, communicate well with them, and who has a clear idea of which direction the EU should develop.”
She explained her new position as Representative for International Affairs and Security as a response to the question: “Who is the European Union? what number should I call?”; i.e. as an important step towards unifying and increasing transparency of the Union’s policy towards countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vicenova further focused on the programme that is key for the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech Presidency of the previous year a successful one.
The Czechs were dealing with the imminent financial crisis; they overcame the crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
Czech representatives in the EU are currently very busy.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis caused the ongoing fermentation.
In addition, a new seven-year EU budget needs to be adopted, which is very difficult given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which less; all these questions are in the upcoming program.
The ambassador recalled the key slogans she brought to Brussels: “On Europe, in a language understood.”
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that no one understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheeses.”
It will also make more effective use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organizations.
Multi-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador argues that the Czechs are considered to be eurosceptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive side of things.
She wants more Czech representatives to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that several factors are to blame for this: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful Presidency of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
“Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and a Slovak joins us, the French next to me says, ‘Hey, what about the assembly, again the Visegrad Group?’ and he is not happy with that.’
In the future, the Union of Vicenov expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policy of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, the idea of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe is more realistic.
“We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone.
“We have a Schengen area, and we already have an institution of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it was said that countries that want to unite, while those that don’t want to stay aside.”
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe," Vitsenova expects.
In this regard, she emphasized the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all matters affecting the EU as a whole should be discussed by all member countries, not just those in the eurozone.
History of Brand:
IBM is entering the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses IMB’s strategy, the closest one will probably be “long-lived.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The longevity of the company was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson the Elder.
He believed in his motto that many world problems could be easily solved if people wanted to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant unfolded (as well as the title of his internal magazine, which IMB began to publish in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means constantly moving towards the future.
IBM survived and flourished for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, even though it was not afraid to change everything around it.
During our first hundred years, it has allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
Over the next hundred years, we hope to even more,” said Samuel J. Palmizano, the company’s current CEO, on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complicated system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of employee care just like Bath in the Czech Republic – IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated system of bonuses for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
IBM’s long-term relationship with consumers is equally advanced.
From the very beginning, the company has found a brilliant application for talented people.It was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, giving it a great choice.
It is consistent with the anti-discrimination strategy and the current plan under which a woman, Virginia Rometti, will replace Palmizano next year.
She worked at IBM for thirty years; now she is the Director of Sales, Marketing and Development.
Over the past few years, IBM has been organizing meetings, online brainstormings, during which many future innovations are emerging.
It is not surprising that there are many ideas - the company employs about half a million people.
Organization with a good reputation
The strong position of the company in the business is provided by a strong internal and external image.
“From the very beginning, from the concept point of view, IBM was more of an organization than a technology company,” said Rosabeth Moss Canter, a Harvard Business School professor and author of the book on IBM.
“IBM is not a technology company, it’s a company that helps solve business problems using technology,” adds Joe Coloney of Forrester Research.
