IBM’s history: from the cheese knife to space flights.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago. Its original name "Corporation of Computing, Tabulation, Record" was quite complicated.
It was named IBM in 1924 and was originally the name of a brand used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future IBM were laid by the merger of four companies, the history of which begins in the 1880s.
They possessed technologies such as the legendary "table clock", i.e. clocks that record the time when employees come and leave work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also headed the board of trustees of the company until 1930.
Flint hired the company’s competitor, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
Then the manager pushed IBM founder into the shadow – Watson’s ideas remain the basis of unwavering corporate culture and individuality.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and sale of various equipment for business - from cheese knives and meat cuts to cash machines.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company began to expand on all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his place in the chair of director was taken by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began developing artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA to control space flights — to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 — human flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - IBM line System/360.
The classic PC, which defined the computer standards of that time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, at the same time buying the consulting division PricewaterhouseCoopers, thereby fully concentrating on consulting and high value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has achieved great success with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make intelligent use of technology in areas where this has not yet been planned, and to improve road conditions and urban governance.
In the field of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM traditions are strong even in our country.
In former Czechoslovakia, the first country to be located simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also runs a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague, where a world-class speech recognition research team also works.
