Travel prices since 1989
Before 1989, only five state travel agencies could operate in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, the travel agencies of the time primarily sold tours to the countries of the Socialist bloc.
Thus, for the holidays, Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia.The Yugoslav regime then turned to the West, which entailed significant restrictions on Czech tourists' trips to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter-invitation from that country was necessary; otherwise individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but you had to either stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have “good friends” at the agency.
And that was not all.
A currency permit was required for trips to the West.It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without currency permission it was impossible to obtain cash (Western currency) for travel to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit persists to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While before 1989 a vacation in the DDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our trips, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia now, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the need to obtain a visa for neighboring Western European countries was abolished, leading to a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not be saturated with trips to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring their own food (conserves, salads, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech krone.After decades, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income grew, which around 1997 led to another important circumstance.
Since 1997, the increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the possibility to book wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually all developed countries except the United States.
The next major event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000.The great demand led to the historically first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries.This winter, flights from the Czech Republic will depart to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the visa requirement for Czech tourists, thus joining the most developed countries of the world forever.
For the first time in history, in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15 thousand crowns per person during their holidays abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
