She rushed to add every swimming pool she liked to her notebook – with important details about the building’s construction and history.
Architectural historian Meeder has explored more than 200 swimming pools – and has now gathered impressions in her recently published book Badefreuden, which includes everything from public pools in Munich to historic swimming palaces in the Black Forest and “functional concrete buildings” in Townshend.
In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited swimming pools in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania and Poland – and one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old author is a true enthusiast of bathing culture.
She has very little enthusiasm for the sport, Meeder says, but in the water it’s different.
The only disadvantage is that swimming fans have to tolerate the blue canvas and the smell of chlorine, while runners can breathe the seductive smell of needle forests or listen to the cheering of birds in the park.
“I once asked myself why swimming pools should always be so awful,” says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
“So I started collecting beautiful swimming pools.”
When the surface doubles the architecture
Swimming in the pool and refined oils in the sauna - the health factor in the bathrooms is so significant, because, according to Meeder, all the senses are stimulated.
And swimming pools can be a real pleasure for the eye, if builders take on such work. "Instead of the floor in the pool you have a surface of water."
"The surface is very transparent, but also reflects the beauty of the entire building."
Everything is visually reflected: high ceilings, colored tiles and tramps.
The 190-page illustrated edition of "The Joy of Swimming" contains valuable information about the architectural and cultural history of health oases - and causes you to want to jump into the water.
Meeder, a reservoir collector, discovered several outstanding specimens during a study in Hungary.
She discovered nitrate-rich water in a karst cave (Cave Bath in Mischolz-Tapolz) and a thermal bath filled with alkaline water in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jasper), as well as magnificent therapeutic baths, such as the 100-year-old Sechen Baths in Budapest.
Of the many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria, on the other hand, there is a stunning view. You can see all of Zurich from the bathroom on the roof or look at the snowed Arlberg from the open pool in St. Anton. And in the steamroom there is a window that allows you to see what is happening on the ski.
Per the most unusual design awaits swimmers in Langenfeld. The Aqua Cathedral in Etzal looks like an UFO just landed in the Alps.
In the winter, the steam of three open shells rises from it, which appear to be quite small against the background of the Ettal Mountains.
Alhambra in Schwarzwald
The pool collector Meeder did not meet the smell of chlorine in every pool.
Many thermal baths smell gray.Arpad baths in Bekeshchab smell so oil that it can be difficult for you to believe that you are in a health source.
The smell is caused by hydrocarbons in alkaline water. The water is almost black from the mud that sticks to the skin as soon as you dive into the pool is a health experience of a certain type.
Iris Meeder, however, at some point was disappointed in her search for beautiful places to swim.When she tried to visit the open swimming pool of the Czech Baths in Lugacovice, she found that the territory was sealed.
The bathrooms, designed by the architect Dushan Yurkovich in 1902, were closed.
When Meeder looked into the viewing windows of the red-white-yellow building in the style of ar-nuvo, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
One of the places where the destruction was stopped by hot tracks is the amazing swimming pool in Schwarzwald – the Palace of Thermal Waters in Bad Wildbad.
The pools have already gone through three stages of construction. You will discover not only neo-Roman elements of the post-building period in 1844, but also the Alhambra-style Moorish hall, added around 1900.
After a thorough reconstruction in 1995, the Thermal Palace – the favorite swimming pool of swimming pool scholar Iris Meeder – and not only because it comes from Schwarzwald.
