21st Century House in Vienna
Pavilion in a New Place
Ingeborg Vinsovsky
The Pavilion of Austria for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, was empty and abandoned.
It is now reopened as an exhibition center.
The Pavilion of Austria, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple shapes, glass halls that boldly expressed faith in technical progress.
Schwanzer's Pavilion won the Grand Prix of Architecture in 1958 for its lightweight steel and glass floating structure.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built the Pavilion of Austria at the next World Exhibition.
Eventually, it became world famous in 1973 with its legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and its sister – a cup-shaped building.
Designed as a temporary exhibition building, the pavilion was moved to the Swiss Garden near the Southern Station of Vienna, converted and opened as the 20th century museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "House of the 20th century" for this reason.
In any case, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it did not have walls to hang works of art on, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna got a new home.
The house was empty since 2001 and its condition was getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krishanitz has so far restored the pavilion, which has been named the "House of the 21st Century" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open its first exhibition on Tuesday evening – in every sense a joyful event.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new initiative.
Husslaine-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a figurative in her youth, who worked at Sotheby’s, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, persuaded politicians and custodians to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations and decided on how the building would be used.
The new museum was to accommodate a permanent exhibition of the Fritz Votruba Foundation, a café and a bookstore along with contemporary art.
Strict control and limited budget
Krishanitz was then the ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Viennese Secession of Joseph Olbrich, and won the contest, but he also studied with Schwanzer at the Viennese University of Technology, and the pavilion was for him "an extremely important place" where he attended exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and knew the challenges facing the building, a building that had already lost some of its majesty and ease when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last reconstruction were much more serious.The building was a “energy absorber,” says Krishanitz.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, glass-fiber-enhanced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced with high-strength safety glass.
The steel pavements of the heat bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors created space for the new use of the building, a burning light well between the building and the street provides lighting – a virtually new building, but still an elegant Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it was before.
All this under strict control of the museum management and with a limited budget.
"We often had to find material that was good, cheap, and would be approved by the museum management," Krishanitz says, pointing to the uneven flooring in the basement.
The building remains flexible and lightweight despite limitations, problems and transformations.
Krishanitz recently noted that the pavilion “from Brussels” was rough – a typical story of “a drop in the city.”
Such an architecture “is not always in place” and yet wants to “stimulate real awareness.”
The 21st-century house is in the right place, as an unexpected luck happened when planning the city. The completely redesigned "Master Station Quarter" with offices and residential properties grows around the Swiss Garden.
A second happy event may occur.The 21st century home may be complemented by the second building of Krishanitz - collector Francesca von Habsburg has acquired the Berlin Temporary Exhibition Hall and isly negotiating with the city about its location nearby in the Swiss Garden.
