Most of the leading risky banks in Europe are not in France or Italy, but in Switzerland.
UBS barely went bankrupt during the financial crisis and has since continuously struggled with one and another crisis.
Now the German must return it to the right course.
Alex Weber probably did not suspect that he would get this role.
In July, after his spectacular departure from the post of head of the Federal Bank, it was announced that in 2013 he would begin to work on the equally spectacular post of Chairman of the Board of Directors of the largest Swiss bank UBS; an unexpected and lucrative career.
Alex Weber was clearly delighted, praising Switzerland for its beauty, UBS for the newly found strength, and made a few friendly remarks to his future colleagues.
“UBS has changed for the better.”
“I look forward to working with Kaspar Filiger and Oswald Grubel.”
But in September, it became clear that everything would be different.
London-based trader UBS surpassed the bank’s security systems and lost about €1.7 billion.
