He suddenly turned out to be responsible for the strategy of the bank, which once again proved that it has long earned the title of "the biggest banking scandal in Europe".
UBS, on the one hand, is very large – until recently it has managed the largest assets in the world – and, on the other hand, has not come out of scandals for years.
It seems that the proud Swiss bank does not save anything.
It all started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had a good reputation.
The bank combined the image of a covert and stable but at the same time agile asset manager with ambitious goals and the aspiration to become the largest player in investment banking.
As a result, in 2007, UBS managed $1.6 billion, thus having more money in the management of wealthy customers than any other bank in the world.
As an investment bank, it has entered the league of the largest banks in the world.
It made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and professor of banking who has long taught at the Institute of Banking at the University of Zurich, explains: “I have always referred to my students UBS as a model of a good bank.”
"Knowing what we know now, you might ask how I could have been so wrong."
He really was very wrong.
It was only in 2007 that it became clear that something was going wrong with UBS.
In the middle of the year, executive director Peter Wuffley – who was considered an outstanding intellectual and equally brilliant banker – left his post unexpectedly.
A few months later, we could guess why he left.
The investment unit of the bank tried to play on substandard securities and was forced to write down billions.
Believe it or not, but UBS has announced a capital increase of 13 billion Swiss francs to cope with the crisis.
The bank has really managed to find investors — but investors that many bankers would have courteously refused until recently — one very opaque Asian sovereign fund from Singapore and one Arab sovereign fund so hidden that even its name has not been disclosed.
It was only the first blow.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to announce new billion-dollar losses, and Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel – the second highest-paid Chairman of the Board of Directors in Switzerland in 2006 – resigned.
Due to a lack of investment during the financial crisis, UBS faced the threat of collapse, and the state had to save it.
The National Bank purchased toxic securities from UBS for an unnamed amount of billions, and the Swiss Confederation paid six billion Swiss francs for a convertible bond with compulsory conversion to become co-owner of the bank.
The whole Switzerland was in shock: the country realized the dramatic consequences of having huge banks set up in a small country.
After all, UBS’ total balance sheet in 2007 was five times greater than all Swiss output (see chart).
“We won’t be able to save UBS a second time,” says banking analyst Geiger.
The second accident occurred shortly after the first.
A few months later, UBS surrendered in a tax dispute with the U.S. and said it was ready to transfer data from wealthy customers who may have been tax evaders with the help of the bank.
UBS also agreed to pay $780 million, consisting of reimbursement of unjustified business revenues plus fines.
UBS thus more or less acknowledged that it was an instrument of tax evasion.
At the same time, UBS has lost what has always been its advantage in the struggle for wealthy customers – the veil of secrecy.
After this scandal, the Swiss banking secret was no longer the same as before.
The Executive Director and the Chairman of the Board of Directors subsequently resigned, and
The money of the customers began.
