Peter Englund’s tense and very good new book, Beauty and Sorrow: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of actors from whom the heart dies.
Here’s a tip on how to read further: carefully cut out this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund tells the story, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, like one of these men and women, you fall off the road and get lost in the mist of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he has written now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as “an anti-historical work.”
There are few known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors, ingenious journalists, or discussions of tactics and combat equipment.
It’s not so much a book about what was, he explains, as a “book about what it looked like.”
"Beauty and Grief" brings together the experience of 20 more or less remarkable men and women from both sides of the front line, from schoolchildren and botanicals to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and staff.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone will get captured, lose a hand or leg, get mad or die.
Their lives flash here like church candles: new ones are added to many others, and some are extinguished at this time.
Mr. Englund’s Book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is also an amendment to the notion that the First World War was only a heavy barricade war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully gives a panorama of other theaters of military action: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
On the soldiers in this book fall beekeepers; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unresolved problem is the cece fly.
It’s an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War covers the lives of these people, like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling of smoke-free dust.
When a canonade is heard nearby, and you are a woman and you are at home with your children, will you stay there or run away?
Anyway, who is it?
Almost no one understands what is happening and why it is necessary to fight in this war.
“The lack of facts,” notes Mr. Englund, “is filled with guesses, assumptions, hopes, fears, obsessive ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
Beauty and Sorrow follows the fate of people like Florence Farmboro, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young seamen of the German Open Sea Fleet.
Their stories are taken mainly from memoirs, letters and other materials already published.
The stories of their lives can be frightening or thrilling, but they are mostly alive thanks to the tiny moments and fragile details collected by Mr. Englund.
Many of them are about deprivations and how to deal with them.
Speaking of the story of a German schoolgirl, he says: "Erzaz, everywhere erzaz."
“Replacement alcohol, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons.”
He continues to talk about erzac food in Germany.
He describes “meat of pressed rice cooked in lamb fat (and decorated with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato skin; shoes cut by a tree.”
He notes that there were "837 registered meat substitutes authorized in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories tell about honor and courage.
One American notices in himself the desire for cruelty and says of war: "You feel that, after all, it's what men were created for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, a evening newspaper or a bestseller and claim that this showcase is civilization and under your sculpted shirt with hips does not hide a barbar."
The British soldier, on the contrary, notices that he is most likely to die and nobody will notice it or be upset.
"When a person accepts the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think that it will happen in front of the public," he writes.
But this is the opposite, terribly similar to “a convicted man who is hanged secretly.”
Other remarks concern the old Europe that is collapsing, and the new forms of fear.
“The conflict became increasingly an economic competition,” writes Mr. Englund, “a war of factories.”
He notes the arrival of what he calls “a new look in the bestselling of the beginning of the century: a beautifully expressive and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-sewed suit, who arranges a massacre sitting at a desk.”
People act in an unpredictable way: low acts are as many as heroism.
Mr. Englund spoke of the soldiers who in every way tried to get away from the prostitutes with a sexually transmitted disease in order to avoid service on the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade in gonorrhea pus, which soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in the hope of getting to the hospital," he writes.
Desperate people rub him in the eyes, often leading to lifelong blindness.
The prose of Mr. Englund, translated from Swedish by Peter Graves, is flexible, but nonchalant, perfectly suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how the war “liberated completely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.”
People start asking why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books on World War I were often indirect, such as Paul Fassell's "The Great War and Modern Memory" or novels such as Erich-Marie Remarque's "On the Western Front Without Changes", rather than exhaustive historical works.
Mr. Englund’s Book is part of this non-shaped pantheon.
His book has the most stunning ending I can remember in non-artistic literature.
I will not tell him.
But it's like he pulled from a book to a page with a list of characters, picked it out of your hands and lit it with a light bulb.
