Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Breivik was an ordinary guy exposing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to committing a mass murder in Norway in July, which killed 77 people, appeared at his first public hearing.
Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was far from alone on the net: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
It’s easy – you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized that it’s easy to get along with them,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of the recently published report on European cyber populism at the British Research Centre DEMOS.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to highlight the demographic group they need with scientific accuracy – something marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team spotted half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pushed them up with ads, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad offered the user a survey with questions about their level of education, attitude toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 participants of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – even without leaving the office.
“It’s an entirely new way of conducting research,” Bartlett says.
Some results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to explore everything in the world – from health issues to social trends that are expressed in ‘Like’, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-updated information” is triggering a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title of the site by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the charm of Facebook is that it gives you the opportunity to study people you can’t approach on the street with a notebook.
"In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to join the party and they’d never accept you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you’re addressing them directly.”
Others say that using this site would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken feats on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who remained silent about it.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as their hostel mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates drunk status too often.
“You can’t solve a problem without identifying it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
“We’ve found a way to identify children at risk that otherwise’t have been detected.”
Facebook is also constantly extracting various types of data about its users.
The site’s data processing team processed statistics on relationships and Valentine’s Day status, midterm voting in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mainly using information that they only have access to – cyber-freedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is monitoring them whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away from you, the site may process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined standards for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think that many users have even thought about what a researcher can observe behind their profiles," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public student Facebook pages.
"As far as they could imagine, it was only between them and their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that the study object is extremely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to find out how much information in the user’s profile and page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selvin says.
That’s why, despite years of technological research, Selvin thinks that a notebook and pen is still the best research tools of those that can be used.
“Nothing can replace going into the real world and communicating with real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social, and most of the social is still happening offline.”
