How to Catch a Lie
A quick look at the latest headlines shows how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Kane is busy challenging sexual harassment charges from several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The administration of the University of Pennsylvania was charged with false testimony because they allegedly concealed that a retired football coach raped boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught when he told U.S. President Barack Obama, with the microphone on, that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner presented himself as a fool by denying his outcry, which was quickly disproved by undeniable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with financial manipulation during a campaign involving hiding off extra-marital relationships.
And again, none of those who lived at the time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of fraud at school and college exams are common.
There were instances when teachers gave students answers to the tests in order to have a good assessment of the results of their activities.
Teachers who have to teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
During a day, research shows you can lie from 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that much of this is a lie for salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting lies or deceiving lies is a necessary skill for everyone, both for personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room-like game, for example, where you need to shout “Fall Out!”, lying detection is a serious direction of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been dismantled.
The liars look in the eyes.
They are not always clogged, swirled, red or swirled.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced liar exposer can get to the truth by observing the structure of claims, mimics, structure of questions, and temporal characteristics.
I’ve spent several years exploring scientific discoveries in the vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lies, and it’s clear that lying detection is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and that helps to navigate in our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel free, controlling their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone’s feelings, that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lie they tell is most commonly obscure).
We also know that if you are perceived as a deceiver, others will feel less guilty by deceiving you.
How do I know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called the “definition of the starting state.”
This helps provide a starting point for evaluating further changes.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly knocking his legs in a normal state, then you will not make unfair accusations when you see his legs knocking in the middle of a meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and non-verbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not as evidence of deception.
Fraudsters can fix the upper part of their body when they try to remember their story, they can put their feet in the direction of the door, bend to the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or demonstrate “relief after the interview” – that exaggerated breath of relief and change of posture when all the difficult questions are behind.
Investigators often falsify the end of the interrogation signal to just look at that relief after the interview.
Pay attention to the speech of your object.
It is known that Scott Peterson gave up and used the past time, claiming that his murdered wife was alive, which led to her searches across the country.
Persuading people may also use distancing in speech: “I didn’t have a sexual relationship with this woman ... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question altogether.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely captured.
Someone may use a “qualification language” when answering a difficult question: “Well... in truth... as far as I know... as far as I know.”
This makes the response more emotional than actual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic tool to reveal a lie, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase everyone’s chances of not becoming a victim of skilled scammers in professional and personal life.
