Mexican Court Approves ‘Transition to Digital Television’ in 2015
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that have encountered the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court has rejected the constitutional claims raised by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which postpones the so-called "digital television transition" from 2021 to 2015, because there were no eight votes needed to cancel it.
A minority of the four ministers, including the Chairman of the Court, Juan Silva Messa, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers by issuing a decree detailing the action for the transition to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected because of the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes needed for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because regulating radio and television programmes is a law-enforced right for the Federal Commission on Telecommunications (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvador, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the House of Representatives held two constitutional debates to disprove the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the meeting of ministers, it was also decided to reject the request of the House of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive power cannot determine by general rules the measures to which the state administration should prepare.
"I also don't think that if this happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, has to do with the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, to manage the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals – one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years – has led to better use of radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality, and more channels.
Delaying the transition, he said, would mean delaying the benefits of digital transformation, which involves meeting societal needs that have not only a technical dimension, “since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These questions, he said, “require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into state executive power.”
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive, despite the presence of highly specialized technical facilities.
From this it cannot be concluded that the government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacan analyze the possibility of counting "voice for voice"
The difference between the first and second seats in the governor’s elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes coming from 879 out of the total of 6,074 protocols.
The possibility of counting “vote-by-vote” is real with regard to this year’s election process in Michoacán, where, according to data obtained from the Preliminary Results Program (PPRV), the difference between first and second place in the governor’s elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes coming from 879 out of the total of 6,074 protocols.
In the light of this, the Chair of the General Council of the Michoacan Election Institute (IMI), Maria de Los Angeles Lyanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, November 9, the electoral body approved a package of principles to align local rules with the federal electoral reform.
As it should be recalled, Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Law on Electoral Rights, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the deadlines specified in the law in the Official Journal of the State, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SJJ) ruled on the constitutional claim raised by the local legislature and called the vote of a representative of the state on constitutional reform "invalid and illegal", as he has no right to "allow or support them."
In an interview on the possibility of “vote-for-vote” Maria de los Ángeles Liaanderal argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council of the IMM it would be possible to submit a partial or full count of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, partial recalculation of one or more electoral urns may be carried out under the conditions that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no protocol of voting and counting of documents in the urn or it is not with the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the protocol.
Furthermore, a total recount of votes in all polling stations may take place when there is indication that the difference between the alleged winner of the elections in question and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to one percent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from a representative of the party and/or coalition that put out the second of the aforementioned candidates.
A total recalculation of votes shall also be made if, at the end of the ordinary count, it is established that the difference between the winner and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate took the second-place, in the event that electoral urns that were taken into account in the partial recalculation will be excluded.
It is worth noting that in such a situation are the elections in Morelia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, not even counting 129 votes out of the total number in the 923 protocol.
