The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the president of Italy tomorrow to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster.
The appointed Italian prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and harmed the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive body will take up its positions.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to reaffirm my full confidence in the ability of our country to get out of this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles were overcome.
“The structure is now well outlined,” he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve the austerity package required by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Based on pressure on Monti to hurry, the volatile markets set Italy’s 10-year BTP bond revenue above 7 percent, a level that Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after meeting with Monti: “We said we will actively support this government.”
We believe this government is Italy’s last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts should lead to a good outcome," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the government majority consisting of technocrats that Monty forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support for reforms that will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and destructive attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has increased pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He will end his series of meetings on Tuesday evening.
Monty was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, which allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a short pause at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the value of Italy’s debt has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Saving Italy with a public debt of €1.8 billion would be too much for today’s euro zone financial defenders.
Monti said his government will exist until the next election scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to reform before scheduling new elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be composed only of technical specialists, proof of their dissatisfaction with the fact that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources said mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicated the attempt to include political figures.
