Quintet included the country on tour in honor of twenty years of career
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream.
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Amant of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to give one of the best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
There’s been more than 20 years of waiting, but the group says it’s also a dream that has become a reality for them to play in this country.
This was a statement by bassist and founder, Jeff Amant, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on a tour in South America to celebrate their 20th anniversary and will make their only stop in Central America on Sunday, 20th.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Los Angeles team The X and the local group Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, a full decoding of which is available online at The Nation.
For your Costa Rica fans, is it a dream that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream fulfilled and for us too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far everything is going well.
I’ve only been to Costa Rica once – on vacation, it’s a beautiful country, and I think we’ll be able to stay there for a few days.
We are very happy to bring our music there.
I’m asking because there’s some commitment to the band; fans live in tension in the days before the concert.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we regret that it took us so long to get here.
Some people, waiting for your concert, treat it as the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played in the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We had some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that brought us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle, as far as these two things are concerned, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua as well as Mexico, these are great places to surf, here’s how we learned about it from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can say that you did a grand show with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for a performance in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there before, we have no limits on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible with the most varied songs; we will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a wide variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does it go?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played for a while, it keeps us in tone and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and so I think it makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour you celebrate 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you have done?
Yes of course.
First, I think none of us ever imagined that we would be in a rock band and the fact that we’ve been doing it for more than 20 years makes it like a dream.
We are delighted with our luck and we are very excited that we can continue to create music together.
We all love each other and love to make music.
We’re happy to drive to places in the world where we’ve always wanted to go.
Everything goes very well for us.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the flower of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We’re good friends with guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when the movement grows out of a group of friends, and that’s unusual.
From time to time, one group appears from one city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups appear at the same time in one city.
We are proud and honored to be part of a group from Seattle.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we’re happy to be friends with all of them and for us it’s an honor to be part of the Seattle sound that turned out.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same composition for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many groups exist.
First, I think we are lucky that we are still alive, and secondly, we care about others.
We’re all very close friends and, thanks to this, we’ve also opened up musical paths that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other’s music, and everything could not have been better.
Your attitude to the word fame was difficult; but thanks to your success you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find balance.
We take care not to be too long on the tour because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for music, it reminds you that you must respect music and what made it, not deciding to be famous and to be a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we’re writing really good songs and it was great at the beginning.
We were the band for almost three years and didn’t release a single album until Andy’s death.
There was a lot of disappointment because it lasted so long, and the most important thing is that we are still close friends with Bruce (Ferweser) and Greg (Gilmore) who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a photo, I think of the incredible person Andy was, and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and more.
He was a wonderful man and we miss him.
The local group Las Robertas will be responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you are familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and so you chose her to discover?
Yes, the producers sent us a few video offers, and it was a band that we liked the most so we can’t wait to see what Las Robertas can offer live, and it should be very exciting.
Why do you constantly change the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
This is a question to Eddie Vedder, so I don’t know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
So many of them.
Among the first to come to mind, Geyser Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramon, John Dow, Paul McCartney, Chuck Duckowski ...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed inining the relevance of the grunge, despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel some sort of detachment from the word grandz.
When I think about it, it reminds me of bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came up at the same time, and if it matters now, I think it’s wonderful because it’s music worth listening to, and teams like Mudhoney are making music now better than ever.
At first your music was darker, but now it has become more positive.
How do you explain this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they may sound a bit positive.
From both, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs were very dark.
I think when you’re growing up and there’s been some kind of trauma in your life and you’ve lost a family member or a friend, these events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
