MSS Announces Obesity Gen Search Program
Social protection leads research into obesity genes in children and young people; it is supported by IPN experts
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which is called the "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence" protocol, which will provide a count of signs associated with overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Medical Research Division in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multi-disciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Center for Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (whether prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children will be conducted every Saturday, from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began to be carried out in the sports center in Quatémoc (in the west of Mexico), and from October 8, the events are held in the sports center in Nassaualkhoiotle (east of Mexico).
Once the target of attracting between 500 and 600 children is reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (North Mexico).
He explained that the aim of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to obesity development and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged between 6 and 14 with the permission of their parents and under their supervision to fill in individual nutritional questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health professionals’ concerns about anxious weight gain among children.
In medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006, it is stated that in just 6 years there was an increase: in the case of boys, 77 percent suffered from obesity, in the case of girls, 47%; in the case of overweight, there was also a significant increase," said MSSI specialist.
He said that the justification of searching for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He that on average a Mexican is 65 percent offspring of American Indians, 30 percent offspring of Europeans, and five percent offspring of Africans, and this condition has affected genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main consequence of obesity genetics is the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can reveal whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated confidentially, the doctors pass it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that need to be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes that provoke overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV, and using transportation on short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sweetened drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid cracks
Raphael Errera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical faculty, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature impacts.
If the signals sent by the road cover were taken into account, about 200,000 holes would need to be repaired for each rainy season in the capital district in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Errera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, and adds that if the process of building andining the asphalted road cover is correct, the number of holes can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture, The Technology View of the Hole, read as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Errera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, like in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus counter the formation of holes.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some with a high molecular mass called asphaltens, and others with a low molecular mass called maltens, which together give the road cover its characteristic viscous and elastic behavior.
The viscous elastic behavior of bitumen lies in the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius itins a solid state, while at very low temperatures bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but varies over the course of the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said the chemical engineering specialist.
The scientist observed that the streets of Mexico are mostly covered with flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is bitumen, made up of small stones lowered into bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is immersed in bitumen.
When driving vehicles and putting effort, this helps the forces to be distributed very well along the road.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, the last layer is placed, which is called a layer of wear, which is made of fine stone, actually sand also immersed in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the wheels of the transport, it should have greater resistance than the asphalt coating and provide road friction.
Being part of the road cover that will receive and spread these efforts, the wear layer also requires a proper thickness, and it is necessary to take into account the material from which it is made.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the soil is wet, water penetrates into the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of there, this causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, consequently, the formation of holes.
When a hole is formed, he said, the wear layer is worn first and only then this affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantly, this is a process that should be paid attention to at the first signs of current repair programs.
Also a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be related to the transport load and it is necessary to ensure compliance with this requirement to prevent the frequent appearance of holes.
Raphael Errera said that much is still to be studied and done about bitumen, such as bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help to repair holes with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
