Russian scientist helped Iran's nuclear program
Russian scientist Vyacheslav Danilenko helped Iran develop a detonator suitable for use in nuclear weapons, a U.S. agency specializing in the field of nuclear danger confirmed on Monday.
The Institute of Science and International Security (ISIS) relies on a recent report from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and other UN agency documents to identify the scientist.
Last week, the IAEA expressed concern about the “possible military aspect” of Iran’s nuclear program.
According to ISIS, which relies largely on IAEA documents, Mr. Danilenko was born in 1934 and worked for 30 years, “starting in the 1960s, at the Soviet military nuclear facility in Chelyabinsk (Ural) and was involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds with explosive methods.”
In 1989 or 1991 he left the center to create a company that produces "nano diamonds" in Kiev.
The financial difficulties of his company led him to contact with the Iranian embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He then collaborated with the Iranian program from 1996 to 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its report, the IAEA mentions "evident signs that Iran's development of the "nuclear detonator system" was contributed by the work of a foreign expert who not only knew the technique well, but who also told the agency that he had worked most of his career on this technology as part of his home country's military nuclear program."
Anti-Muslim Crimes Increase by 50%
According to the FBI statistics released on Monday, the number of anti-Muslim crimes increased by 50 percent between 2009 and 2010, while other forms of racial and religious violence decreased slightly or remained unchanged over the same period.
According to these figures, the total number of cases of violence against Muslims grew from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, which is equivalent to an increase of 49%, compared with a 13% increase in cases of violence against Catholics, a 4% decrease in attacks on Jews and a 14% overall increase in the number of crimes on religious grounds.
The total number of hate crimes, according to the FBI, increased very slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47,3% were motivated by racial differences and 20% were religious differences.
Following a decline in 2009, there is concern that the number of these crimes is rising again, human rights organization Human Rights First stressed, “the increase in violence against Muslims is significant,” the organization added in an official statement.
“Human Rights First has long emphasized that acts of violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, should be treated as serious human rights violations,” added one of the leaders of the organization, Paul Legander.
"The U.S. government can and should do more to deal with these crimes, he adds, believing that this can be done by improving police reports on hate crimes."
“Hate-based crimes” in federal law are a legacy of a period of civil rights struggle.
This law was adopted after Martin Luther King’s death to punish acts of violence related to race, color, religion, nationality and today’s sexual orientation.
Twitter is changing its platform and becoming similar to Facebook
On Monday, the microblogging site Twitter made changes to the presentation of its platform that will allow its users, in particular, to see the activity of those they follow, which makes the service similar to Facebook.
The new “activity” tab and a different “name” tab make it easier and more direct to track the activity of other “Twitter” users, the Internet users whose messages (“tweets”) you are tracking, and those who are tracking yours.
This allows you to know if they will post messages, if they will sign up for new accounts, if they will have selected messages, etc.
This new Twitter formula was tested "on a small percentage of users in August" before being widely used across the network on Monday, Caroline Penner told AFP.
Twitter, which has long been known as intuitively rather unclear and as using rather vague terms (RT for posting someone else’s temptation, #followfriday for recommending to follow other users), mostly pleasing experienced users, opens itself thus to a wider audience, presenting users with something closer to the popular social networks Facebook and Google+.
In the network, users discussed this innovation with the help of "tweets" on the Internet.
“It’s useless, obsessive, and too much like Facebook.”
Functional activity will help me better track certain elements of my Twitter stream, wrote @dannykronstrom.
Austrian
The introduction of the "golden rule" of the budget
The leadership of the large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write the budgetary "golden rule" into the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid a possible reduction by rating agencies of Austria's state credit rating (a triple A).
Chancellor Werner Faymann personally announced this decision at the end of a meeting of the Council of Ministers, while Austria’s public debt is 74.6%, which is significantly higher than the upper threshold of the rate of 60%, set by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria's solvency fell by only one point, from AAA to AAA+, we would have to pay interest by three thousand million euros more each year, said Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister from Christian Democrats Michael Spindlegger.
Thus, Austria is fulfilling the requirement of the Eurozone summit on October 26 in Brussels; heads of state and government have called for budget deficits to be cut by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced government accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The ruling, adopted by the Austrian government, resembles the “German model” as Germany was the first European country to adopt this “rule”.
By 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of the federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of GDP, and the lands, like communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to make public debt fall below the 60% mark stipulated by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
