"Japan is struggling to rebuild itself" after the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region (north-east), Noda stressed, fearing that this growth in the yen would kill the fragile germ of recovery.
The world’s third-largest economic power resumed growth in the third quarter by -1,5% compared to the previous quarter – for the first time in a year, thanks to the growth of exports and consumption of households affected by the disaster.
But the prime minister feels that the high price of the yen does not reflect the “fundamental economic indicators of Japan.”
Finance Minister Zhong Azumi called on the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened its two-day monetary policy council meeting on Tuesday, to take all necessary steps to weaken the yen.
