The Energy Policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be decided after a short discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings are an occasion to reflect on the share and place of nuclear energy.
The dispute will not be fruitful until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options have been examined.
France must build its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
We are now 7 billion people on the planet, and demographic developments will result in the need for electricity doubling by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill the growing fossil deficit in order to continue producing electricity consistently, not forgetting the crucial need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to tackle climate imbalance – a topic that has disappeared from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That’s why Germany remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case for Belgium, which depends on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are determined to continue their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one plant to its kit, resuming the construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on Three Mile Island.
Although Germany’s model based on renewable energy is sometimes cited as an example, reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, aggravated by increased demand for imported gas, in particular from Russia, and a jump in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be noticeable.
We should take the example of Denmark.
The European champion in turbine construction, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; due to which carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the average in Europe.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than the French households.
In a globalized economy, as the price of energy is a key competitive factor and the key to servicing industrial equipment on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Consequently, any significant reduction in nuclear energy will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power illusory.
The price most French refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the energy policy of the country has made it possible to create an industry of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect.
Heavily export-oriented, it attracts a whole multitude of international trade-specialized small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to abandon nuclear power, it would have to donate a large number of these enterprises and lose 6 billion euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to work for sixty years if it was planned to shut down its manufacturer?
To solve the energy equation, it is necessary to acknowledge that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear energy,ining the highest level of safety is undoubtedly a vital issue.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control of existing energy centers such as Flamandville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is widely recognized, are full of the same obsession with safety.
Over the past 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences for humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the device of the reactor and the unforgivable human error led to a tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the crash occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it has learned from the two previous ones.
The result of this step and the cooperation between security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, presents a project to counter such phenomena.
Since it is considered by all energy professionals who want to build the reactor, stopping its construction in Flamandville will be a great gift to rivals Areva and EDF, paving the way for them to win leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and prejudice to prevail in a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a benefit to the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various sides – the overload of police, judicial and administrative services subordinated to the policy of numbers and the compatibility of this policy with France’s self-proclaimed status as a “state of human rights.”
Then there was an administrative harassment of foreign students, which came to the news when the Minister of the Interior ("Libération" of May 23) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, stoneworkers and waiters."
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The right and the left agree on this.
On the right-wing side, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 stated that “900,000 unemployed people will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers,” and on the left-wing side by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France “cannot accept the poor from all over the world.”
The difference is in generosity.
In 2005, fear of the invasion of the territory of the country by the Polish water pipeline horde was felt by both the left and the right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity they will show to immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande limited himself to banality, saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem.”
This view of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing the latest data on immigration (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Determine Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Publishing House, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that host immigrants.
Restricting immigration leads to slowing growth and lowering employment.
Fears of the influence of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace local workers, especially low-skilled, provoking lower wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants complement much more than replace local workforce by doing jobs that lack local workforce.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local workforce, and the most skilled are in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on salaries
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between locals and immigrants leads to the fact that the arrival of immigrants positively affects the salaries of local workers.
Perry estimated that a 1% increase in immigration flows would result in a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among American Nobel laureates a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, while Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net income to social security systems, providing an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labour Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will bring a net profit (income minus expenses) of an average of 150,000 euros to the state budget during his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his term of office was going to "tooth" to get stuck in the missing points of growth.
The mentioned teeth, which were used to scare away immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to understand European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition, but at the same time fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the twentieth century it survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to organize a vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the time of Napoleon the "Little", it is known that it comes from the superficiality of thinking.
Whilst universal voting is a prerequisite for democracy, it is not a sufficient prerequisite for democracy and may even become a “instrument of suppression,” as Republican philosopher Ethan Wasro said.
No, democracy requires much more – public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of authorities, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is primarily a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this regard, the palynody of a true-false Greek referendum will have a double exposing effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious change of policy and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality must be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the frontline of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, according to many, Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We won’t win anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organized as necessary and in a chaotic order.
A "card-blank" for an absolute European monarch or a jump with the legs bound into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we are not dreaming of a guillotine blade, but of the implementation – jointly, clearly and continuously – of choice and democracy, this time at a pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many of them will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis – the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is subjected to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but Europe as a whole is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to restore the management of the European project to the sovereignty of the people.
Because only by working together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of everyone’s debt, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
To get out of the crisis will require decisions at a pan-European level, and they cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy without leading us to a catastrophe.
After a long discussion of this proposal, the Socialists and Jacques Delors are now all demanding a European economic government.
Let it so.
But to imagine it without a stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has come into existence is another madness and a new impasse.
We must begin a new phase of European construction.
In order to establish a republic in France, it was necessary to “create” Republicans.
The revolution of interests would not be enough.
This lesson remains in force.
We must build a united Europe on an economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a real European people’s sovereignty.
To create Europe, let us create Europeans.
Contactless chip cards are becoming increasingly widespread.
The world exhibition of chip cards opens on Tuesday in Wilpent near Paris in an atmosphere of optimism.
In fact, 2011 will end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessors (banking cards, phones with SIM-cards), exceeding, according to Eurosmart, 6 thousand million units.
The most important is the contactless technology sector, which allows you to pay for public transportation or purchases simply by holding a map over a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, up from 320 million a year earlier.
Their share will grow in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and will account for 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is now moving forward in contactless payments.
Approximately 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this feature, and they are accepted by 75,000 terminals.
France starts from a more modest position: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are in circulation.
But the big shops are boosting the pace.
This year, Carrefour issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass.
To move to a higher speed, it is necessary for banks to supply their customers with equipment.
“Two major organizations in France have pledged to systematically distribute bank cards adapted for contactless use among their customers in the future,” said Gerard Neboui, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing payments using mobile phones.
But this is only the first stage in the development of the future means of payment, that is, the mobile phone.
So far, only a few devices are equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary for such transactions.
“They were postponed.
“But they should really fly out next year.”
“We expect global sales to range from 80 to 120 million units in 2012,” explains Mark Burten, head of Eurosmart.
Banks are moving forward.
Yesterday, Crédit Agricole announced the conduct of the experiment from December to June next year in Cannes.
Approximately 200 customers and employees will be equipped with iPhone devices that provide contactless payments.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also said yesterday that it is preparing to launch a market offer that allows its customers to pay through mobile phones.
