North Stream, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly along the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the orchestra’s performance and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte together turned a symbolic valve controlling the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Through the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will be supplied to Western Europe each year via the first pipeline of 1,224 km, connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be completed by the end of 2012, providing a total supply of 55 thousand million cubic meters of gas, equivalent to the total consumption of France.
The possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will actually allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding the passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose part of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia, threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop comparing the Nord Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting on an alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This is a politically sensitive issue.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and wealthy Western countries, which consume large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
“This pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” said Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the Gazprom heads who were present in large numbers at Lubmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the mine fields that remained from the Second World War.
“One hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
There were also many steps needed to protect fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, without breaks throughout its length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers rejected it because Sweden was not delighted that the Russian state company would permanently settle off its shores.
"In the event of an accident, we will cut off the flow of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
So, in case of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to the designers who designed seams designed to run only once every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline will be carried out by a submarine robot, which pulls the ship, for external observation, as well as an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
The cigar-like apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and is pushed forward by the flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any metal deformation.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is carried out only by its pressure.
It is 200 bar at departure and 100 bar at arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was commissioned to build and operate the pipeline.
Its headquarters is in Tsuga, Switzerland, where taxation is favorable.
Gazprom then leased the company for 20 years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas will actually be transported,” says Jens Müller.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30% shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez will invest around 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay off their costs, because Gazprom takes on all the risks.
The gas pipeline leads from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin to a sandy shore planted with needles.
Valves of 4.5 meters of height form the exit terminal of gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour, and 6 million in 2012.
The Moleskine Brand Notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste of writing.
He has the smell of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize by the rectangular black cover, by rubber, by yellow-white pages, as if yellowed with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, has decided to launch the sale of design notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took over the responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The note is inspired by the old manufacturing technique, moleskin - a lacquered cotton fabric used, for example, to cover benches.
It is claimed that this type of notepad is highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought into line with today’s taste an old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success has arrived.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales grew by 25% to 12.7 million units.
We are far from the production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Establishing a profile of a typical buyer is difficult, because the notebook attracts an entrepreneur, a student and a freelancer equally.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notes in Fnac bookstores, stores in the centers of small cities and has been able to gain widespread fame.
"We followed the spirit of time and this new need for writing, despite the emergence of email," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This distinctive cultural trait accompanies the development of Moleskine; recently the brand organized the “Road around” exhibition, where architects and artists demonstrated their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched coverings with a leopard drawing on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags.
A success that gave rise to envy: In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which inscribed a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for disabled people begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is still twice the average, namely 19% versus 9% for the general population.
It disappointed?
“No,” emphasizes Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes the Disability Employment Week.
“In 15 years, significant progress has been made.”
At that time, the proportion of unemployed was not two, but three times more.
“But there is still a lot of work ahead.”
There are still many obstacles to disability in employment.
Among them are older people: 37% older than 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for disabled people versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the core of the problem,” said Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association on behalf of Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “imagined people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally handicapped.”
The result – private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of disabled workers set in the law adopted in 1987.
The latest known figures from 2008 are 2.6%.
“Today we’re about 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that don’t comply with the law.
Evidence: The number of "taxable" entities, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 entities (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law that raised the tax has put a lot of pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in awareness, in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with employees between 20 and 49 have disabled workers versus 82% of organizations with employees between 100 and 199.
